Abstract¶

For this project, I am using the Football Manager 2020 Dataset on Kaggle. This is a dataset based on the popular video game Football Manager where the player acts as a manager of a top football club and the data in the game is based on real life players' attributes. The specific dataset I have chosen has 136,000 rows and 64 columns, which include both player attributes such as Age, Height, Club, Nationality, and player performance statistics in categories such as Vision, Pace, Crossing, and Shooting.

This is quite a broad and in depth dataset, so for my project I would like to hone in on the specific goal of predicting a player's market value. I will accomplish this using a supervised machine learning approach applying regression algorithms. Data preprocessing steps will include handling missing values, scaling numerical features, and encoding categorical variables. Feature selection will be focused on the attributes deemed most relevant to a player's market value. Model evaluation will be based on metrics such as MSE and R-Squared.

The expected benefits of this project are very applicable in the real world, as it would allow a football team's manager or scouting department to locate undervalued football players and pursue them in hopes of bettering their squad, or potentially selling them on for profit in a few years.

from pyspark.sql.types import NumericType

# Identify numerical columns
numerical_columns = [field.name for field in data.schema.fields if isinstance(field.dataType, NumericType)]

# Compute correlations with 'Value'
correlations = []
for col in numerical_columns:
    if col != 'Value':  # Skip self-correlation
        corr_value = data.corr('Value', col)
        correlations.append((col, corr_value))

# Sort correlations by absolute value, descending
sorted_correlations = sorted(correlations, key=lambda x: abs(x[1]), reverse=True)

# Display the top 10 correlated features
print("Top 10 Features Correlated with Value:")
for feature, corr in sorted_correlations[:10]:
    print(f"{feature}: {corr:.3f}")

from pyspark.sql.functions import col, mean, when, count

# Check for missing values
data.select([count(when(col(c).isNull(), c)).alias(c) for c in data.columns]).show()

# Fill missing values for numerical columns with the mean
numerical_columns = ['Wage','CA', 'PA', 'Cmp', 'Bal', 'Tea', 'Ant', 'Cnt', 'Pen', 'Wor']
for col_name in numerical_columns:
    mean_value = data.select(mean(col(col_name))).collect()[0][0]
    data = data.fillna({col_name: mean_value})

# Fill missing values for categorical columns with mode
categorical_columns = ['Position', 'Club']
for col_name in categorical_columns:
    mode_value = data.groupBy(col_name).count().orderBy('count', ascending=False).first()[0]
    data = data.fillna({col_name: mode_value})

from pyspark.ml.feature import MinMaxScaler, StringIndexer, OneHotEncoder, VectorAssembler

# Scale numerical features
scaler_input = ['Wage','CA', 'PA', 'Cmp', 'Bal', 'Tea', 'Ant', 'Cnt', 'Pen', 'Wor']

# Drop the existing 'numerical_features' column if it exists
data = data.drop('numerical_features','scaled_features','Position_index','Club_index','Position_encoded', 'Club_encoded')

# Assemble the numerical features
assembler = VectorAssembler(inputCols=scaler_input, outputCol="numerical_features")
data = assembler.transform(data)

# Apply MinMaxScaler
scaler = MinMaxScaler(inputCol="numerical_features", outputCol="scaled_features")
scaler_model = scaler.fit(data)
data = scaler_model.transform(data)

# Encode categorical features
indexer = StringIndexer(inputCols=['Position', 'Club'], outputCols=['Position_index', 'Club_index'])
data = indexer.fit(data).transform(data)

encoder = OneHotEncoder(inputCols=['Position_index', 'Club_index'], outputCols=['Position_encoded', 'Club_encoded'])
data = encoder.fit(data).transform(data)

from pyspark.ml.tuning import ParamGridBuilder, CrossValidator
from pyspark.ml.evaluation import RegressionEvaluator

# Set up parameter grid for tuning
param_grid = (ParamGridBuilder()
              .addGrid(lr.regParam, [0.2, 0.01])
              .addGrid(lr.maxIter, [10, 40])
              .build())

# Initialize cross-validation
cross_val = CrossValidator(estimator=lr,
                           estimatorParamMaps=param_grid,
                           evaluator=RegressionEvaluator(labelCol="Value", predictionCol="prediction", metricName="rmse"),
                           numFolds=3)  # 3-fold cross-validation

# Train the model using cross-validation
cv_model = cross_val.fit(train_data)

# Get the best model
best_model = cv_model.bestModel

# Make predictions with the best model
predictions = best_model.transform(test_data)

# Show predictions
predictions.select("prediction", "Value", "features").show(5)

from pyspark.sql.functions import col, when

# Deduplicate original_data and predictions
original_data = original_data.dropDuplicates(["Name"])
predictions = predictions.dropDuplicates(["Name"])

# Join predictions with original_data
predictions_with_names = predictions.join(original_data, on="Name", how="inner")

# Calculate value_diff only for cases where prediction > Original_Value
predictions_with_names = predictions_with_names.withColumn(
    "value_diff",
    when(col("prediction") > col("Original_Value"), col("prediction") - col("Original_Value")).otherwise(0)
)

# Filter players where value_diff > 0 to only include undervalued players
undervalued_players = predictions_with_names.filter(col("value_diff") > 0)

# Sort by value_diff in descending order
undervalued_players = undervalued_players.orderBy(col("value_diff").desc())

# Show top 5 undervalued players
undervalued_players.select("Name","Age", "Original_Value", "prediction", "value_diff").show(5)

Limitations¶

This Dataset is from the 2020 edition of the game, so these players are now four years older and four years further into their careers than the statistics know. This is an obvious limitation, as the goal of the analysis would be to find current undervalued players. However, the fact that this is old data allows us to look into how some of these projected players have performed in the four years since this data and analyze whether the predictions made by the model would have been helpful. Lucas Hernandez was already an established player but has continued to thrive and plays for Bayern Munich, the biggest club in Germany and is a member of the French National team. Marcelo Pitaluga is rostered to Liverpool, one of the biggest clubs in England and is still only 20. Malik Tillman is an American international who plays for PSV Eindhoven in the Netherlands and has 5 goals in 14 appearances, as well as making 17 appearances for the US Men's national team at only 22. A few other names that jump out as current big names are Oscar Bobb, who at only 19 is already making appearances for Manchester City, and Pervis Estupinian, who at 25 is a star player for Brighton. In the four years since the dataset was published, a number of the undervalued players have already lived up to their potential and this gives me confidence in the model's performance.

Future Work¶

If I were to continue down this path, one of the other things I would like to investigate using this dataset would be predicting a player's best position based on their attributes. This would be a similar approach as there is a column for best position and I would be able to take a supervised learning approach. Often with young players a manager can struggle to find their best position and it is very common to see a player break into the first team as a left back and eventually become a left wing once the manager knows more about the player. Two massive names in the game that spring to mind are both Gareth Bale and Bukayo Saka who broke in as left backs and were seen as more defensive, yet once they were established as left wingers became incredily prolific and efficient goalscorers. By looking at the dataset and analyzing correlation between specific attributes and positions, I would like to develop a skillset for specific positions on the pitch and then match younger players to those skillsets to determine what their best position is likely to be.

Conclusion¶

In this project I used the Football Manager 2020 dataset. I initially looked at the distrubtion of player values across the entire dataset, and then looked at a correlation matrix of all the different columns in the dataset. From there, I found the 10 factors that correlated most with a player's value, and trained a linear regression model based on those. After dropping all player's with a 0 value, I split the dataset into test and train and trained the model, acheiving a Root Mean Squared Error of 1,713,698.3712479246. This is relatively reasonable, considering player's values can range from 0 to 250 million. The model also acheived an R^2 value of 0.605106729867781. After this, I looked at a parameter grid to fine tune the model and concluded the best regParam to be 0.2 and the best maxIter to be 40. This model gave me an RMSE of 1,713,698.326279434 and an R^2 value of 0.6051067505922616, so slightly better, albeit not a huge difference. Once I had trained this model, I ran it on the entire dataset to find a predicted value for each player. I then compared this predicted value with the player's listed value to find out which players had the largest difference. Finally, I decided to filter out older players so I could locate young potentially undervalued prospects in the dataset. Overall, I think my results were pretty accurate, as four years on from this dataset, I recognize many of the young players my search returned.
